  <head>
    <title>
      RDF XML Surface Syntax
    </title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>
      Simplified XML Syntax for RDF
    </h1>
    <p>
      <a href="mailto:jonathan@openhealth.org">Jonathan Borden</a> Tufts
      University School of Medicine, <a href="http://www.openhealth.org">The
      Open Healthcare Group</a> This version: <a
      href="http://www.openhealth.org/RDF/RDFSurfaceSyntax-20010617.html">June
      17, 2001</a>
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href="http://www.openhealth.org/RDF/RDFSurfaceSyntax.html">Latest
      version</a>
    </p>
    <p>
      A simplified XML syntax for RDF is proposed. Its major differences
      with RDF 1.0 are:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        namespace = <a
        href="http://www.openhealth.org/RDF/RDFSurfaceSyntax">http://www.openhealth.org/RDF/RDFSurfaceSyntax</a>
      </li>
      <li>
        defined as tree regular expression
      </li>
      <li>
        attribute aboutQ=&quot;ex:name&quot; accepts QName as value indicating
        subject
      </li>
      <li>
        attribute resourceQ=&quot;ex:value&quot; accepts QName as value
        indicating object
      </li>
      <li>
        rdf:parseType=&quot;Resource&quot; is default
      </li>
      <li>
        The subject or object of a statement may be either a URI reference, a
        qualified name, a quantified variable, another statement or a
        collection of statements.
      </li>
      <li>
        ?x defines a quantified variable
      </li>
    </ol>
    <h2>
      XML Syntax
    </h2>
    <p>
      The XML syntax for RDF 1.0 can be described in terms of a tree
      regular expression. This form can be thought of as expressing constraints
      on the XML Infoset which arises when parsing an RDF document. The
      advantage of expressing the syntax in this form over EBNF, is that a tree
      regular expression (e.g RELAXNG/TREX schema <a
      href="http://relaxng.org">http://relaxng.org</a> ) already takes into
      account the rules of XML syntax + XML namespaces, e.g. correctly handles
      namespace prefixes, empty elements, mixed content, whitespace, attribute
      ordering etc. Such schemata are also described as &quot;hedge regular
      expressions&quot; or &quot;hedge automata&quot; <a
      href="http://www.oasis-open.org/cover/hedgeAutomata.html">http://www.oasis-open.org/cover/hedgeAutomata.html</a>.
    </p>
	<rddl:resource
		xlink:role="http://relaxng.org/ns/structure/0.9"
		xlink:arcrole="http://www.rddl.org/purposes#schema-validation"
		xlink:href="http://www.openhealth.org/RDF/RDF1.rng">
    <p>
      The tree regular expression schema for RDF 1.0 is available <a
      href="http://www.openhealth.org/RDF/RDF1.rng">here</a>. This schema
      handles several proposed updates such as the requirement that the
      &quot;rdf:about&quot; and &quot;rdf:ID&quot; attributes be
      prefixed/qualified.
    </p>
	</rddl:resource>
	<rddl:resource
		xlink:role="http://relaxng.org/ns/structure/0.9"
		xlink:arcrole="http://www.rddl.org/purposes#schema-validation"
		xlink:href="http://www.openhealth.org/RDF/RDF.rng">
    <p>
      A tree regular expression for the proposed syntax is available <a
      href="http://www.openhealth.org/RDF/RDF.rng">here</a>.
    </p>
	</rddl:resource>
    <p>
      The <em>obj</em> pattern is described thus:
    </p>
    <p>
      &lt;define name=&quot;obj&quot;&gt;
      <br />
        &lt;choice&gt;
      <br />
         &lt;ref name=&quot;description&quot;/&gt;
      <br />
         &lt;ref name=&quot;container&quot;/&gt;
      <br />
        &lt;/choice&gt;
      <br />
       &lt;/define&gt;
    </p>
    <p>
      The <em>description, container, idAboutAttr, idAttr</em> patterns are
      described thus:
    </p>
    <p>
      &lt;define name=&quot;description&quot;&gt;
      <br />
        &lt;choice&gt;
      <br />
          &lt;element name=&quot;Description&quot;&gt;
      <br />
           &lt;optional&gt;
      <br />
               &lt;ref name=&quot;idAboutAttr&quot;/&gt;
      <br />
           &lt;/optional&gt;
      <br />
           &lt;optional&gt;
      <br />
               &lt;ref name=&quot;bagIdAttr&quot;/&gt;
      <br />
           &lt;/optional&gt;
      <br />
           &lt;zeroOrMore&gt;
      <br />
               &lt;ref name=&quot;propAttr&quot;/&gt;
      <br />
            &lt;/zeroOrMore&gt;
      <br />
          &lt;/element&gt;
      <br />
          &lt;ref name=&quot;typedNode&quot;/&gt;
      <br />
        &lt;/choice&gt;
      <br />
       &lt;/define&gt;
    </p>
    <p>
       &lt;define name=&quot;container&quot;&gt;
      <br />
        &lt;choice&gt;
      <br />
            &lt;ref name=&quot;sequence&quot;/&gt;
      <br />
            &lt;ref name=&quot;bag&quot;/&gt;
      <br />
            &lt;ref name=&quot;alternative&quot;/&gt;
      <br />
        &lt;/choice&gt;
      <br />
       &lt;/define&gt;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lt;define name=&quot;idAboutAttr&quot;&gt;
      <br />
        &lt;choice&gt;
      <br />
            &lt;ref name=&quot;idAttr&quot;/&gt;
      <br />
            &lt;ref name=&quot;aboutAttr&quot;/&gt;
      <br />
            &lt;ref name=&quot;aboutQAttr&quot;/&gt;
      <br />
        &lt;/choice&gt;
      <br />
       &lt;/define&gt;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lt;define name=&quot;idAttr&quot;&gt;
      <br />
         &lt;attribute name=&quot;rdf:ID&quot;&gt;
      <br />
            &lt;data type=&quot;ID&quot;/&gt;
      <br />
         &lt;/attribute&gt;
      <br />
       &lt;/define&gt;
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      An example:
    </p>
<pre>
         &lt;r:RDF xmlns:r=&quot;http://www.openhealth.org/RDF/SurfaceSyntax&quot;
                  xmlns:ex=&quot;http://example.org/ex&quot;&gt;
           &lt;r:Description r:aboutQ=&quot;ex:Jon&quot;&gt;
            &lt;ex:says&gt;
             &lt;ex:color r:aboutQ=&quot;ex:sky&quot; r:resourceQ= &quot;ex:blue&quot;/&gt;
            &lt;/ex:says&gt;
           &lt;/r:Description&gt;
         &lt;/r:RDF&gt;
   
</pre>
    <p>
      =&gt;
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        [ex:Jon ex:says [ex:sky ex:color ex:blue]]
      </li>
    </ul>
